"Spielhagen R.F., Werner K., Sørensen S.A., Zamelczyk K., Kandiano E., Budeus G., Husum K., Marchitto T.M., Hald M.","Enhanced modern heat transfer to the arctic by warm atlantic water",2011,"Science","331","6016",,"450","453",,,10.1126/science.1197397,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79251548547&partnerID=40&md5=90c914b8a25913be413e4a90da0d6d07","Academy of Sciences, Humanities, and Literature, 53151 Mainz, Germany; Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences (IFMGEOMAR), 24148 Kiel, Germany; Department of Geology, University of Tromsø, 9037 Tromsø, Norway; Alfred Wegener Institute of Polar and Marine Research, 27515 Bremerhaven, Germany; Department of Geological Sciences, Institute of Arctic and Alpine Research, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309, United States","Spielhagen, R.F., Academy of Sciences, Humanities, and Literature, 53151 Mainz, Germany, Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences (IFMGEOMAR), 24148 Kiel, Germany; Werner, K., Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences (IFMGEOMAR), 24148 Kiel, Germany; Sørensen, S.A., Department of Geology, University of Tromsø, 9037 Tromsø, Norway; Zamelczyk, K., Department of Geology, University of Tromsø, 9037 Tromsø, Norway; Kandiano, E., Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences (IFMGEOMAR), 24148 Kiel, Germany; Budeus, G., Alfred Wegener Institute of Polar and Marine Research, 27515 Bremerhaven, Germany; Husum, K., Department of Geology, University of Tromsø, 9037 Tromsø, Norway; Marchitto, T.M., Department of Geological Sciences, Institute of Arctic and Alpine Research, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309, United States; Hald, M., Department of Geology, University of Tromsø, 9037 Tromsø, Norway","The Arctic is responding more rapidly to global warming than most other areas on our planet. Northwardflowing Atlantic Water is themajor means of heat advection toward the Arctic and strongly affects the sea ice distribution. Records of its natural variability are critical for the understanding of feedback mechanisms and the future of the Arctic climate system, but continuous historical records reach back only ∼150 years. Here, we present a multidecadal-scale record of ocean temperature variations during the past 2000 years, derived from marine sediments off Western Svalbard (79°N). We find that early-21st-century temperatures of Atlantic Water entering the Arctic Ocean are unprecedented over the past 2000 years and are presumably linked to the Arctic amplification of global warming.",,"advection; global warming; heat transfer; marine sediment; sea ice; Arctic; arctic climate; article; Atlantic Ocean; greenhouse effect; heat transfer; priority journal; sea ice; sediment; Svalbard and Jan Mayen; water temperature; Arctic; Atlantic Ocean; Svalbard; Svalbard and Jan Mayen",,,,,,"Screen, J.A., Simmonds, I., (2010) Nature, 464, p. 1334; Graversen, R.G., Mauritsen, T., Tjernström, M., Källén, E., Svensson, G., (2008) Nature, 451, p. 53; Chylek, P., Folland, C.K., Lesins, G., Dubey, M.K., Wang, M.M., (2009) Geophys. Res. Lett., 36, pp. L14801; Comiso, J.C., Parkinson, C.L., Gersten, R., Stock, L., (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L01703; Divine, D.V., Dick, C., (2006) J. Geophys. Res., 111, pp. C01001; Kaufman, D.S., (2009) Science, 325, p. 1236; Rudels, B., Jones, E.P., Anderson, L.G., Kattner, G., (1994) The Polar Oceans and Their Role in Shaping the Global Environment, pp. 33-46. , O. M. Johannessen, R. D. Muench, J. E. Overland, Eds. American Geophysical Union, Washington, DC; Schauer, U., Fahrbach, E., Osterhus, S., Rohardt, G., (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. C06026; Bonnet, S., De Vernal, A., Hillaire-Marcel, C., Radi, T., Husum, K., (2010) Mar. Micropaleontol., 74, p. 59; Hebbeln, D., Dokken, T., Andersen, E.S., Hald, M., Elverhøi, A., (1994) Nature, 370, p. 357; Dokken, T.M., Hald, M., (1996) Geology, 24, p. 599; Spielhagen, R.F., (2004) Quat. Sci. Rev., 23, p. 1455; Hald, M., (2007) Quat. Sci. Rev., 26, p. 3423; Lamb, H.H., (1977) Climate: Present, Past and Future, 